# 10-emc2305-fan-pid.rules — start fan-pid.service when the EMC2305 PWM fan
# controller binds on the i2c bus.
#
# Why this exists:
#   The fan-pid.service unit has WantedBy=multi-user.target plus a DT-only
#   board-gate condition. On the LS1046A Mono Gateway DK the EMC2305 lives
#   on i2c-7 at address 0x2e and is bound by the kernel's `emc2305` i2c
#   driver asynchronously when the i2c bus probe runs. That probe RACES
#   with multi-user.target activation: when systemd evaluates the unit
#   before the device exists, the previous `ConditionPathExistsGlob=` on
#   the driver's bound-device symlink would silently drop the unit and
#   systemd would NEVER re-evaluate it later. Observed 2026-05-11: at
#   login time both conditions were satisfied yet `journalctl -u
#   fan-pid.service` showed `-- No entries --`.
#
# This rule guarantees the daemon starts the moment the device actually
# binds, regardless of whether multi-user.target won the race or not. The
# unit's `Conflicts=fancontrol.service` and the daemon's own startup
# idempotency (it cleanly takes over the PWM register from any prior
# writer) make a duplicate `start` from both paths harmless: systemd will
# coalesce the request, and at most one fan-pid process ever runs.
#
# Match scope:
#   - SUBSYSTEM=="i2c"          : i2c device events only
#   - ACTION=="bind"            : driver→device bind moment (NOT just "add",
#                                 which fires before the driver binds and
#                                 would race the same way as the unit did)
#   - DRIVER=="emc2305"         : the kernel's EMC2305 PWM fan controller
#                                 driver; matches only the device the daemon
#                                 actually controls
#
# We do NOT match on KERNEL=="7-002e" so this rule survives any future
# board revision that moves the chip to a different i2c bus or address.
# The driver name is the stable invariant.
ACTION=="bind", SUBSYSTEM=="i2c", DRIVER=="emc2305", \
    TAG+="systemd", ENV{SYSTEMD_WANTS}="fan-pid.service"